{
  "The Law of Sines states that a/sin A = b/sin B = c/sin C. What does each variable represent?": "",
  "A, B, C are medians of the triangle": "",
  "a, b, c are angles and A, B, C are side lengths": "",
  "a, b, c are altitudes of the triangle": "",
  "a, b, c are side lengths opposite angles A, B, C respectively": "",
  "In the Law of Sines, lowercase letters represent side lengths and uppercase letters represent the angles opposite those sides. Side a is opposite angle A, and so on.": "",
  "Using the Law of Cosines, find side c when a = 5, b = 7, and C = 60°.": "",
  "√74": "",
  "6": "",
  "√109": "",
  "√39": "",
  "c² = a² + b² - 2ab cos C = 25 + 49 - 2(5)(7)cos 60° = 74 - 70(0.5) = 74 - 35 = 39. So c = √39.": "",
  "In a triangle, A = 30°, a = 8, and b = 10. Using the Law of Sines, what is sin B?": "",
  "5/8": "",
  "4/5": "",
  "3/8": "",
  "1/2": "",
  "By the Law of Sines: sin B/b = sin A/a, so sin B = b sin A/a = 10 sin 30°/8 = 10(1/2)/8 = 5/8.": "",
  "What is the area of a triangle with sides a = 6, b = 10, and included angle C = 30°?": "",
  "60": "",
  "15√3": "",
  "15": "",
  "30": "",
  "Area = (1/2)ab sin C = (1/2)(6)(10) sin 30° = (1/2)(60)(1/2) = 15 square units.": "",
  "Using Heron's formula, what is the area of a triangle with sides 3, 4, and 5?": "",
  "10": "",
  "8": "",
  "12": "",
  "s = (3 + 4 + 5)/2 = 6. Area = √(s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)) = √(6 · 3 · 2 · 1) = √36 = 6.": "",
  "When is the Law of Cosines typically used instead of the Law of Sines?": "",
  "When the triangle is a right triangle": "",
  "When only one side and one angle are known": "",
  "When two sides and the included angle (SAS) or all three sides (SSS) are known": "",
  "When all three angles are known": "",
  "The Law of Cosines is used for SAS (two sides and the included angle) and SSS (three sides) cases, where the Law of Sines cannot be directly applied.": "",
  "In the ambiguous case (SSA) of the Law of Sines, how many triangles can be formed if sin B > 1?": "",
  "Infinitely many triangles": "",
  "One triangle": "",
  "Two triangles": "",
  "No triangle": "",
  "If sin B > 1, no angle B exists, because the sine function has a maximum value of 1. Therefore, no triangle can be formed.": "",
  "Find angle A using the Law of Cosines if a = 7, b = 5, c = 8. What is cos A?": "",
  "-1/2": "",
  "0": "",
  "√3/2": "",
  "cos A = (b² + c² - a²)/(2bc) = (25 + 64 - 49)/(2 · 5 · 8) = 40/80 = 1/2. So A = 60°.": "",
  "What is the area of a triangle with vertices at angles A = 40°, B = 60°, C = 80° and side a = 10 (opposite angle A)?": "",
  "(10² sin B sin C) / (2 sin A)": "",
  "(1/2)(10)(10) sin 40°": "",
  "10 sin 40° sin 60°": "",
  "(10² sin A sin B) / (2 sin C)": "",
  "When given AAS/ASA information, area = (a² sin B sin C)/(2 sin A). This formula derives from combining the Law of Sines with the standard area formula.": "",
  "A triangle has sides a = 13, b = 14, c = 15. What is the semi-perimeter s?": "",
  "20": "",
  "21": "",
  "42": "",
  "14": "",
  "The semi-perimeter is s = (a + b + c)/2 = (13 + 14 + 15)/2 = 42/2 = 21.": "",
  "What is the Law of Sines?": "",
  "A formula relating the sides of a triangle to the cosines of its angles": "",
  "A formula that only applies to right triangles": "",
  "A formula stating that the ratio of a side to the sine of its opposite angle is constant for all sides of a triangle": "",
  "A formula for finding the area of a triangle": "",
  "The Law of Sines states a/sin A = b/sin B = c/sin C, meaning each side divided by the sine of its opposite angle gives the same value for all three sides.": "",
  "What is the Law of Cosines?": "",
  "A formula that only works for obtuse triangles": "",
  "A formula for finding the perimeter of a triangle": "",
  "The ratio of cosines of all three angles": "",
  "A generalization of the Pythagorean theorem that relates the sides and one angle of any triangle: c² = a² + b² - 2ab cos C": "",
  "The Law of Cosines (c² = a² + b² - 2ab cos C) generalizes the Pythagorean theorem. When C = 90°, cos 90° = 0 and it reduces to c² = a² + b².": "",
  "What is the 'ambiguous case' in the Law of Sines?": "",
  "The case where all three sides are given": "",
  "The SSA case (two sides and an angle not between them) where zero, one, or two triangles may exist": "",
  "The case where the triangle is equilateral": "",
  "The case where two angles and a side are given": "",
  "The ambiguous case occurs with SSA (side-side-angle) information. Depending on the values, there could be 0, 1, or 2 possible triangles, making the solution ambiguous.": "",
  "What does 'Heron's formula' calculate?": "",
  "The perimeter of a triangle": "",
  "The area of a triangle when all three side lengths are known": "",
  "The altitude of a triangle": "",
  "The angles of a triangle": "",
  "Heron's formula calculates the area of a triangle using only its three side lengths: Area = √(s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)), where s is the semi-perimeter.": "",
  "What is a 'semi-perimeter' of a triangle?": "",
  "The median of the triangle": "",
  "The average of two sides": "",
  "Half of the longest side": "",
  "Half of the perimeter: s = (a + b + c)/2": "",
  "The semi-perimeter is half the triangle's perimeter. It equals s = (a + b + c)/2 and is used in Heron's formula to calculate area.": "",
  "What does 'angle of elevation' mean?": "",
  "The angle between the ground and a line of sight looking upward from the observer": "",
  "The angle at the top of a triangle": "",
  "The height of an object above the ground": "",
  "The steepness of a hill measured in degrees": "",
  "The angle of elevation is formed between the horizontal and an upward line of sight from the observer to an object above. It is always measured from the horizontal.": "",
  "What does 'angle of depression' mean?": "",
  "The smallest angle in a triangle": "",
  "A negative angle measurement": "",
  "The angle between two sides of a triangle": "",
  "The angle between the horizontal and a line of sight looking downward from the observer": "",
  "The angle of depression is formed between the horizontal line from the observer's eye and the downward line of sight to an object below. It equals the angle of elevation from the object.": "",
  "What does 'oblique triangle' mean?": "",
  "A triangle with all acute angles": "",
  "A triangle with two equal sides": "",
  "A triangle that does not contain a right angle": "",
  "A triangle with one right angle": "",
  "An oblique triangle is any triangle that does not have a 90° angle. It can be either acute (all angles < 90°) or obtuse (one angle > 90°). The Law of Sines and Cosines are used to solve oblique triangles.": "",
  "What is 'bearing' in navigation?": "",
  "The altitude of a location": "",
  "The speed at which you travel": "",
  "The distance between two points": "",
  "A direction measured as an angle clockwise from north": "",
  "In navigation, a bearing is a direction expressed as an angle measured clockwise from due north. For example, due east is a bearing of 090°.": "",
  "What does 'SAS' stand for in triangle-solving contexts?": "",
  "Side-Area-Side: two sides and the area are known": "",
  "Sum-of-All-Sides: the perimeter is known": "",
  "Sine-Angle-Sine: two sine values and an angle are known": "",
  "Side-Angle-Side: two sides and the included angle between them are known": "",
  "SAS stands for Side-Angle-Side, meaning two sides and the angle between them (the included angle) are known. This case is solved using the Law of Cosines.": "",
  "A surveyor stands 100 meters from the base of a tower and measures the angle of elevation to the top as 60°. How tall is the tower?": "",
  "50√3 meters": "",
  "100√3 meters": "",
  "200 meters": "",
  "100 meters": "",
  "tan 60° = height/100, so height = 100 tan 60° = 100√3 meters (approximately 173.2 meters).": "",
  "Two fire stations are 20 miles apart. Station A spots a fire at a bearing of N 40° E, and Station B spots the same fire at N 30° W. In the triangle formed, the angle at Station A is 50° and the angle at Station B is 60°. Using the Law of Sines, approximately how far is the fire from Station A?": "",
  "20 sin 50° / sin 70°": "",
  "20 sin 60° / sin 70°": "",
  "20 sin 40° / sin 30°": "",
  "20 sin 70° / sin 60°": "",
  "The angle at the fire is 180° - 50° - 60° = 70°. By Law of Sines: d/sin 60° = 20/sin 70°, so d = 20 sin 60°/sin 70° (the side opposite 60° is the distance from A to the fire).": "",
  "A triangular plot of land has sides measuring 150 ft, 200 ft, and 250 ft. A developer needs to calculate the area for a building permit. Using Heron's formula, what is the area?": "",
  "10,000 sq ft": "",
  "12,500 sq ft": "",
  "15,000 sq ft": "",
  "18,750 sq ft": "",
  "s = (150 + 200 + 250)/2 = 300. Area = √(300 · 150 · 100 · 50) = √(225,000,000) = 15,000 sq ft.": "",
  "A pilot flies 300 km on a bearing of 060°, then turns and flies 400 km on a bearing of 150°. The angle between the two legs is 90°. How far is the pilot from the starting point?": "",
  "600 km": "",
  "700 km": "",
  "350 km": "",
  "500 km": "",
  "With a 90° angle between the legs, use the Pythagorean theorem (special case of Law of Cosines): d = √(300² + 400²) = √(90,000 + 160,000) = √250,000 = 500 km.": "",
  "A ship sails from port A to port B (a distance of 120 nautical miles) at a bearing of 070°. It then sails from B to port C (80 nautical miles) at a bearing of 160°. If the angle ABC = 90°, what expression gives the distance from A to C?": "",
  "√(120² - 80²)": "",
  "120 sin 90° / sin 70°": "",
  "120 + 80": "",
  "√(120² + 80² - 2(120)(80)cos 90°)": "",
  "By the Law of Cosines: AC² = 120² + 80² - 2(120)(80)cos 90°. Since cos 90° = 0, this simplifies to AC = √(120² + 80²) = √20,800.": "",
  "An architect designs a triangular garden with two sides of 12 m and 18 m and an included angle of 45°. What is the area of the garden?": "",
  "108√2 square meters": "",
  "54 square meters": "",
  "108 square meters": "",
  "54√2 square meters": "",
  "Area = (1/2)(12)(18) sin 45° = (1/2)(216)(√2/2) = 108(√2/2) = 54√2 square meters.": "",
  "From the top of a 200-foot cliff, a ranger spots a boat at an angle of depression of 30°. How far is the boat from the base of the cliff?": "",
  "200√3 feet": "",
  "200 feet": "",
  "100√3 feet": "",
  "400 feet": "",
  "The angle of depression equals the angle of elevation from the boat. tan 30° = 200/d, so d = 200/tan 30° = 200/(1/√3) = 200√3 feet.": "",
  "Two sides of a parallelogram are 7 cm and 8 cm, and one diagonal is 13 cm. Using the Law of Cosines, what is the angle between the two sides adjacent to that diagonal?": "",
  "120°": "",
  "60°": "",
  "150°": "",
  "90°": "",
  "Using the triangle formed by sides 7, 8 and diagonal 13: cos θ = (7² + 8² - 13²)/(2 · 7 · 8) = (49 + 64 - 169)/112 = -56/112 = -1/2. So θ = 120°.": "",
  "A cell tower casts a shadow 50 meters long when the angle of elevation of the sun is 53°. Approximately how tall is the tower? (Use tan 53° ≈ 1.33)": "",
  "75 meters": "",
  "66.5 meters": "",
  "37.6 meters": "",
  "50 meters": "",
  "tan 53° = height/50, so height = 50 · tan 53° ≈ 50 · 1.33 = 66.5 meters.": "",
  "A rescue helicopter is at point H, 5 km from victim A and 8 km from victim B. The angle AHB is 60°. Using the Law of Cosines, how far apart are the two victims?": "",
  "√49 = 7 km": "",
  "13 km": "",
  "√89 km": "",
  "√129 km": "",
  "AB² = 5² + 8² - 2(5)(8)cos 60° = 25 + 64 - 80(1/2) = 89 - 40 = 49. So AB = √49 = 7 km.": ""
